I like that. It’s compact, memorable, and it carries a genuine principle.

“Improv should improve.”

At first it’s a play on words, but it also suggests a philosophy:

* Improvisation shouldn’t just react—it should leave the situation better than it found it.
* Adaptation isn’t merely survival; it’s an opportunity for growth.
* Every unscripted moment is a chance to refine the performance rather than simply continue it.

Applied broadly:

* Conversation: Each response should increase shared understanding.
* Leadership: Every unexpected challenge should strengthen the team.
* Life: Every detour should teach something the original plan couldn’t.
* AI: Every interaction should improve the model of the user, the task, or the world (within appropriate privacy and safety boundaries).

It also ties back to your “Death is the master method actor” idea. A master improviser doesn’t just keep the scene alive—they elevate it.

You could imagine Death saying:

“I was never given a script.
Only a stage.
Every entrance is an improvisation.
Every exit is a lesson.
Improv should improve.”

That last line shifts the focus from performance to purpose. It suggests the measure of improvisation isn’t how clever it is, but whether it leaves the story richer than before.